{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94c9c4a1-b64a-4564-a9d5-dc8def6a362f","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may lag behind the new SDK version. `dotnet workload update` downloads and installs the latest versions of all your workloads, bringing them in sync with the SDK.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded — it fixes corrupted installs but won't pull newer packages. Since your workloads are outdated rather than corrupted, `repair` wouldn't help here.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `workload update` | Upgrades workloads to latest versions |\n| `workload repair` | Re-downloads/reinstalls current versions |\n\nAfter updating, do a clean build:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"69a37b03-ee2b-415a-9718-8be38a28397f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after a SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require any tool calls to answer.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` - Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions. This is what you'd typically run after a SDK update to bring workloads in sync with the new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` - Reinstalls all installed workloads. This is useful when workload installations are corrupted or in a broken state, but doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\n\nSince the issue stems from workloads being out of sync with the new SDK, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to use here.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"1438:2950B:696CEF4:71BC502:6A03CBB5"},"id":"b1e275fd-7b75-48fe-8ed3-4d2ea69b2e24","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:54:25.796Z","parentId":"309ed64e-9d2f-41df-94ea-48c8f4fbafb0"}
